<!DOCTYPE MAN SYSTEM "../../man.dtd">
<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>horner  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 1993  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="horner"> polynomial/rational evaluation  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>horner(P,x)   </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>P  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : polynomial or rational matrix
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>x  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : real number or polynomial or rational
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    evaluates the polynomial or rational 
    matrix <VERB>P = P(s)</VERB> when the variable <VERB>s</VERB> of the 
    polynomial is replaced by <VERB>x</VERB>:
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>horner(P,x)</VERB>=<VERB>P(x)</VERB>
  </P>
  <P>
    Example (Bilinear transform): Assume <VERB>P = P(s)</VERB> is 
    a rational matrix  then the rational matrix 
    <VERB>P((1+s)/(1-s))</VERB> is obtained by <VERB>horner(P,(1+s)/(1-s))</VERB>.
  </P>
  <P>
    To evaluate a rational matrix at given frequencies use 
    preferably the <VERB>freq</VERB> primitive.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
s=poly(0,'s');M=[s,1/s];
horner(M,1)
horner(M,%i)
horner(M,1/s)
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
